BOTULISM, AVIAN - USA (02): (MICHIGAN) WATERFOWL
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 12 Aug 2014
Source: Record-Eagle [edited]
http://www.record-eagle.com/news/local_news/article_5667c548-0672-56ef-8acc-259fb0e07323.html


About 30 dead ducks dotted beaches along the east arm of Grand Traverse Bay [Lake Michigan, Michigan, USA] in the last few weeks.

Department of Natural Resources (DNR) officials sent the waterfowl, all mallards, to a laboratory where they tested positive for botulism, a paralytic condition caused by a toxin. Birds with botulism typically are unable to hold up their heads and ultimately drown. [This condition is often called "limber neck." - Mod.TG]

The birds were infected with type C botulism, a toxin that naturally occurs in soil. Experts attributed the impacted birds to elevated lake levels this year [2014].

"It's over the area that hadn't been water-covered in the past couple years," said Katie Keen, a wildlife technician at the DNR. "The ducks wouldn't be feeding in that area if it didn't have water."

The botulism [in this case] does not pose a threat to humans, but Keen said dogs and other pets should be kept on leashes and away from dead animals to avoid ingesting the toxin.

The dead birds were found on the shore near the North Shore Inn and the Pointes North Beachfront Resort Hotel on U.S. 31 [Traverse City, Michigan].

Keen urged anyone who sees a dead duck to call the Traverse City DNR offices.

[Byline: Michelle Merlin]

